Scenario 2: Pressing Play/Pause -> playback advancing frames

High-level connection(s) in `MainWindow::setupConnections()`:
  - `connect(ui->playPauseButton, &QToolButton::toggled, this, [this](bool checked) { setPlayButtonsState(checked); });`
  - Secondary button mirror wired identically.
  - `MainWindow::setPlayButtonsState(bool playing, bool blockSignals)`:
      - `ui->playPauseButton->setChecked(playing);` (mirrors)
      - sets the icon
      - IMPORTANT: `if (playing) ui->videoLoader->play(); else ui->videoLoader->pause();`

Call trace (detailed):

1. User toggles `playPauseButton` (or `playPauseButton_2`)
   -> `QToolButton::toggled(bool checked)` emitted
   -> lambda in `MainWindow::setupConnections()` invoked:
      - Calls `MainWindow::setPlayButtonsState(checked)`

MainWindow::setPlayButtonsState(bool playing, bool blockSignals=false)
  - Optionally `blockSignals` to true to avoid reentrancy when mirroring (but default false here).
  - Update checked state of both buttons, update icon.
  - If `playing`:
      - Calls `ui->videoLoader->play();`
    Else:
      - Calls `ui->videoLoader->pause();`

VideoLoader::play()
  - Guard: `if (!isVideoLoaded() || m_isPlaying) return;`
  - If `currentFrameIdx >= totalFramesCount-1 && totalFramesCount > 0`:
      - `seekToFrame(0, true);`   // resets to start, suppressEmit=true so the seek won't immediately emit `frameChanged`
  - If `currentFrameIdx == -1 && totalFramesCount > 0`:
      - `seekToFrame(0, true);`
  - Set `m_isPlaying = true;`
  - `updateTimerInterval();` -> sets `playbackTimer` interval based on FPS and playback speed.
  - `playbackTimer->start();`
  - Emit `playbackStateChanged(true, m_playbackSpeedMultiplier);`

Important: `playbackTimer` is connected in constructor to:
  - `connect(playbackTimer, &QTimer::timeout, this, &VideoLoader::processNextFrame);`

VideoLoader::processNextFrame()
  - Guard: `if (!m_isPlaying || !isVideoLoaded()) return;`
  - If `currentFrameIdx < totalFramesCount - 1`:
      - `int nextFrame = currentFrameIdx + 1;`
      - Branch:
        Path A: `m_frameCache && m_frameCache->contains(nextFrame)` true
           - `displayFrame(nextFrame);`  // default suppressEmit = false, so `frameChanged` will be emitted in displayFrame
        Path B: frame not cached
           - `m_pendingSeekFrame = nextFrame;`
           - If `m_frameLoaderManager`: call `m_frameLoaderManager->resetPrioritiesForCurrentFrame(nextFrame, s_preloadRadius);`
             and `preloadAdjacentFrames(nextFrame, s_preloadRadius);`
           - Do NOT perform synchronous disk read here; rely on background loader to call `onFrameLoaded`
  - Else (we are at last frame):
      - call `pause();` which sets `m_isPlaying = false; playbackTimer->stop(); emit playbackStateChanged(false, ...)`

If Path A (cached) -> VideoLoader::displayFrame(nextFrame) flow follows (see Scenario 1 Path A), eventually emits `frameChanged(nextFrame, currentQImageFrame)` which goes to MainWindow::updateFrameDisplay and others. After the paint finish, next timer tick -> processNextFrame again -> next frame.

If Path B (not cached) -> `m_pendingSeekFrame` set and background requests made; when background loads the frame it emits `frameLoaded` and VideoLoader::onFrameLoaded is called, and because `m_pendingSeekFrame == frameNumber` it does:
  - set `currentFrameIdx = frameNumber;`
  - emit `frameChanged(currentFrameIdx, currentQImageFrame);`
  - update()
  - NOTE: Since `processNextFrame` didn't call `displayFrame` synchronously, the play timer continues running; on the next timer tick `processNextFrame()` will see `currentFrameIdx` was updated by `onFrameLoaded` so will progress to nextFrame+1 etc. If `onFrameLoaded` was too slow, `processNextFrame` might set another `m_pendingSeekFrame` again for the next frame.

Edge cases observed in code:
  - `VideoLoader::play()` resets to frame 0 when at end, with `seekToFrame(0, true)` -> suppressEmit true meaning first display will NOT emit `frameChanged` immediately. However, background cache may supply the frame and then `onFrameLoaded` will emit `frameChanged`.
  - `seekToFrame(..., true)` used from `play()` prevents immediate double emission during play start; later on the timer the progression will emit frames as usual.
  - If a synchronous `videoCapture.read()` fails while playing, `displayFrame` will call `pause()` to stop playback. Playback can be paused automatically on frame read errors.

Listeners receiving `frameChanged` during playback:
  - Same as in Scenario 1: `MainWindow::updateFrameDisplay`, `MainWindow::updateMiniLoaderCrop`, CacheStatusWidget, MiniLoaders, etc.

